<h2>Ruby on Rails</h2>
<p>This website was created with <%= link_to "Ruby on Rails 3.1", "http://www.rubyonrails.org" -%>. The Ruby on Rails community is great, and has many open source tools, some of which have been used in the construction of this site.</p>

<h3>Technologies used include:</h3>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Ruby 1.9.2</li>
<li><%= link_to "Devise", "https://rubygems.org/gems/devise" -%>, for user management / authentication</li>
<li><%= link_to "OmniAuth", "https://rubygems.org/gems/omniauth" -%>, for the "Sign in with Google/Twitter" links</li>
<li><%= link_to "Formtastic 2.0", "https://rubygems.org/gems/formtastic" -%>, for easy, and awesome, form generation</li>
<li><%= link_to "Show For", "https://rubygems.org/gems/show_for" -%>, for easy, and awesome, pages display a resource (account, transaction)</li>
<li><%= link_to "RABL", "https://rubygems.org/gems/rabl" -%>, for our API</li>
<li><%= link_to "RSpec", "https://rubygems.org/gems/rspec" -%>, for testing</li>
<li><%= link_to "Machinist", "https://rubygems.org/gems/machinist" -%>, for object factories (for use in testing)</li>
<li><%= link_to "HAML", "https://rubygems.org/gems/haml" -%>, but primarily for layouts and forms (following the philosophy of <%= link_to("HAML sucks for content", "http://chriseppstein.github.com/blog/2010/02/08/haml-sucks-for-content/") -%>)</li>
</ul>
</p>

